\f0\fs24 \cf0 <$Scr_Ps::0>
\f1\fs32 The 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 unit-factor method
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  or the 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 unity bracket method
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  is a widely used method for unit conversions using the rules of algebra. This method utilizes\cb3  the fact that any number or expression can be multiplied by one (unity) without changing its value\cb1 .  The advantage of this method is that it explicitly accounts for units, rather than treating a conversion factor as a 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\i\fs32 magic number
\f0\i0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32 .\
To use this method, conversion factors are expressed as fraction equal to 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\i\fs32 one
\f0\i0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32 , and multiplied against the original value while keeping careful track of the units in each term. Multiplying a value by a unit-factor and canceling any dimensional units appearing in both the numerator and denominator will express the original quantity in different units. \
For example, since 
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 \\inch\{1\} = \\cm\{2.54\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32 , dividing both sides by 
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 \\inch\{1\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  inch gives the unit-factor<me> 1 = \\left[\\frac\{\\cm\{2.54\}\}\{\\inch\{1\}\}\\right]</me>.  The fraction bar in this term can be read as <q>per</q>, so this unit-factor says that there are <q>2.54 centimeters per inch</q>.\
To convert 
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 36
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  inches to cm, just multiply by 
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 36
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  inches by the appropriate unit-factor, and cancel the inch units that appear in both the numerator and denominator.\
<me>\\inch\{36\}  \\times \\left[\\frac\{\\cm\{2.54\} \}\{\\inch\{1\}\}\\right] =  36 \\cancel\{\\text\{ in\}\} \\times \\left[\\frac\{2.54 \\text\{ cm\}\}\{\\cancel\{1 \\text\{ in\}\}\}\\right] = \\cm\{91.44\}</me>\
To convert from cm to inches, use the reciprocal of this unit-factor, which is also unity.\
<me>\\cm\{100\}  \\times \\left[\\frac\{\\inch\{1\}\}\{\\cm\{2.54\} \}\\right] =  100 \\cancel\{\\text\{ cm\}\} \\times \\left[\\frac\{1 \\text\{ in\}\}\{2.54 \\cancel\{\\text\{ cm\}\}\}\\right] = \\inch\{39.37\}</me>\
Thus 
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 \\yd\{1\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  (
\f0\fs24 \cf4 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f4\fs32 \\inch\{36\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
